## Description
The **ComplexIf **operator returns a value depending on the result of the defined conditional expression. It is possible to define the expression using one or more inputs and a combination of logical operators.

## Input
**Input**

**Data type**

**Description**

**in0**

Any

The data that you want to use in the boolean expression

**in1**

Any

N-th input, containing the data that you want to use in the boolean expression

## **Output**
**Output**

**Data type**

**Description**

**out0**

Any

The value defined in the settings; it may be:

- Data specified by the user

- One of the inputs available for the operator

- No value

## 
> Important

Data types linked to **inâ€¦ **inputs must correspond to data types allowed in the expression.

## Settings
![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- In the **Inputs **section, click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Add**) to add an input node to the list.

- In the **Conditions **section:

In the **Boolean condition **text area, define the conditional expression that you want to apply, using the available input node names and boolean operators.

> Note

The available boolean operators are:

**AND **

- **OR **

- **NOT**

- **&gt;=**

- **&lt;=**

- **&gt;**

- **&lt;**

- **=**

- **)**

- **(**

- **!**

-  From the **Output if true **drop-down menu, select the input node linked to the data that you want to output to **out0 **if the expression is true.![](data:image/png;base64,)

-  From the **Output if false **drop-down menu, select the input node linked to the data that you want to output to **out0 **if the expression is false.![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Tip

Click![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Add item**) at the bottom of the drop-down menu to add a custom value to the list, then click ![](data:image/png;base64,) to confirm.![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Click **Apply **to confirm.

> Tip

To rename an input node, click on its name to edit it.

To remove an input node from the list, move your mouse over it and click ![](data:image/png;base64,) 	in the **Action **col umn; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Special cases
In special cases, the operator behaves as follows:

Case

Behavior

**NULL input (no input)**

The operator considers a NULL input as an empty string. The system logs a warning event.
